⚙️ Guidance to the Reader: VP Coaching on Maintaining Discipline
	1.	Establish the Operating Rhythm Immediately
	•	Start with flight check before any delivery begins.
	•	Don’t defer rituals — build them into day 0.
	2.	Be Consistent, Even When Pressured to Skip
	•	Skipping risk review or QA council once invites drift.
	•	Use disciplines as non-negotiables; clarity is your armor.
	3.	Protect Time for Governance, Not Just Delivery
	•	Allocate capacity (15–20%) for meetings, dashboards, reviews.
	•	Governance overhead is cost; don’t “steal” governance time later.
	4.	Rotate Ownership, But Keep Accountability
	•	Different roles can facilitate rituals (QA lead, DM, architect), but one role always owns follow-through.
	•	Use RACI to clarify who drives each ritual.
	5.	Use Dashboards to Fuel Rituals, Not Replace Them
	•	Use metrics and alerts as conversation starters, not answers.
	•	In meetings, review deviations and next-step decisions, not raw slides.
	6.	Evolve the Playbook — Don’t Fix It Once
	•	After each phase or project, review which rituals worked, which need tweaking.
	•	Reflect in retros and governance forums, then revise the playbook.
	7.	Fight Alert Fatigue by Escalating Only When Thresholds Hit
	•	Use a thin set of signal alerts; escalate only when thresholds are breached.
	•	For less-severe deviations, use “watcher mode” in dashboards.
	8.	Align Operational Governance to Steering Cadence
	•	Link weekly/monthly reviews with Steering agenda — ensure escalation paths are clear.
	•	Let strategic decisions degrade from operational patterns, not surprise.

From the Field: “Early in my career, I ran daily meetings that grew into 90-minute status reviews — we killed momentum. Later I learned: daily reviews must be lean, with deeper reviews reserved for weekly ritual.”

